******
[1] New Jersey: suspected
Date: Fri 7 Sep 2012
Source: NJ.com [edited]
http://www.nj.com/warrenreporter/index.ssf/2012/09/several_deer_found_dead_in_har.html


As many as 3 deer were reported dead of unknown causes this week, which experts say could make Harmony Township the latest place in N.J. to see epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD).

Larry Ragonese, a spokesman for the the state Department of Environmental Protection Division of Fish and Wildlife, said the deer could have died as result of epizootic hemorrhagic disease, a common viral disease in deer that is contracted from the bite of a species of midge known as _Culiocoides sonorensis_.

If the deer are found with the virus, this will be just the 2nd case in the state this year. The only confirmed case was in Salem County late last month [Aug 2012].

Ragonese said that the deer are currently being tested for the disease. It will take about 2 weeks to get results, he said. Not transmittable by contact, to either people or deer, the disease is only spread by infected midges. An outbreak of infected midges usually stems from mudflats near water. If an infected midge bites a deer, [the deer] could get the disease.

"We don't know if those deer we were told about died with EHD or for other reasons," Ragonese said.

He described signs of the disease as deer that seem to be behaving strangely. They could be staggering, unsteady and drooling with eyes that are glazed or glassy. These deer might not respond the way they typically would and can sometimes lose their fear of humans. Deer found dead with no apparent wounds or found in or near a body of water may also have the virus.

There were no deer found with the virus in Warren County last year [2011], although some were found nearby in Hunterdon County. Other possible cases have been reported in Cape May, Gloucester and Camden counties this year, although these have not been confirmed by laboratory testing.

"It's something that can occur anywhere in the state if you get the right ingredients," Ragonese said.

The disease is not considered to be a public health issue. It cannot be transmitted to people, and people are not at risk by handling infected deer, being bitten by infected midges or eating infected deer meat, although the Division of Fish and Wildlife strongly advises against consuming meat from any animal that appears ill.

