******
[3] Ohio
Date: Wed 12 Sep 2012
Source: HudsonHubTimes.com [edited]
http://www.hudsonhubtimes.com/news/article/5214845


State wildlife and animal health officials have confirmed localized outbreaks of a common white-tailed deer disease in 8 Ohio counties, including Ashtabula, Columbiana, Geauga, Holmes, Paulding, Portage, Ross and Summit, according to Bethany McCorkle, interim chief of communications for the Ohio Department of Natural Resources.

An earlier report of bluetongue disease in Hudson was incorrect, she said.

Ohio Department of Agriculture's Animal Disease Diagnostic Laboratory confirmed that of 20 samples, 13 deer had epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD). State animal health officials stress EHD occurs annually in deer herds across North America.

Bluetongue, a similar hemorrhagic disease, has been known to occur throughout the USA and Canada, but should not be confused with EHD. There are no cases of bluetongue disease confirmed in Ohio, McCorkle said.

White-tailed deer contract EHD from the biting midges, which typically live near water. White-tailed deer, along with mule deer, elk, bighorn sheep and pronghorn antelope are susceptible to the disease.

The disease is not spread from deer to deer or from deer to humans, according to McCorkle. Once infected, deer show symptoms within 5 to 10 days. Infected deer initially lose their appetite and fear of people, grow progressively weaker, often salivate excessively and become unconscious. Many deer die within 36 hours of the onset of symptoms.

Midges can also spread EHD among cattle and sheep. These outbreaks may occur at the same time deer are being impacted. However, this is not a case of the disease spreading from deer to livestock or vice versa, but is an indication that the biting midges are present in large enough numbers to spread the disease.

State wildlife officials stress hunters this fall should report deer that appear to be sick or diseased to their local wildlife officer. Although this disease does not affect humans nor impact the safety of consumed deer, any deer that appear unhealthy should never be taken for human food.

